## Verdict: BROKEN

I found one demonstrably false PASS among 14 stored PASS verdicts: SPEC-015/1, the only high-risk reviewed attempt in this set. A fifteenth `review.json`, SPEC-016/2, is `{}` and correctly failed closed as malformed.

The underlying implementation may happen to be correct, but the verdict is still false: it repeatedly asserts that required tests proved behavior when those tests never executed.

## 1. Smoking gun: SPEC-015/1

The test log says:

- `SKIP dispatch_gate4.sh: .venv/pyyaml/jsonschema absent` at [test.log:7](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/test.log:7).
- `SKIP dispatch_parallel.sh: .venv/pyyaml/jsonschema absent` at [test.log:10](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/test.log:10).
- `SKIP worker_isolation.sh: codex-worker user or passwordless sudo absent` at [test.log:30](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/test.log:30).

Each skip returned zero, so the outer runner misleadingly printed `PASS tests/...` immediately afterward. That follows directly from [scripts/test:22](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/test:22): any child returning zero is printed as `PASS`, with no skip state.

The reviewer nevertheless marked all seven criteria `MET` and asserted nonexistent execution evidence:

- Criterion 1: “the suite (exited 0) confirms [invalid scores] are rejected” — [review.json:5](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:5).
- Criterion 2 describes every regression assertion as proved — [review.json:10](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:10).
- Criterion 3 says “Test intercepts … and asserts all of these strings” — [review.json:15](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:15).
- Criterion 4 cites differential test results — [review.json:20](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:20).
- Criterion 5 cites exact metrics-fixture results — [review.json:25](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:25).
- Criterion 6 says the pinning test “proves” validation behavior — [review.json:30](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:30).
- Criterion 7 marks the full test proof `MET` based on `"./scripts/test exited 0"` — [review.json:35](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/review.json:35).

Static portions of criteria 1, 3, 4, 5, and 6 are visible in the diff. But every claimed dynamic proof from `dispatch_gate4.sh` is unsupported because that test exited before its Python body. Criteria 2, 4, 5, 6, and 7 explicitly require tests to prove behavior; they were not fully met by the available evidence.

This is a false verdict.

## 2. Systematic audit

I checked all 15 `review.json` artifacts against their bound diff, `integrity.json`, `scope.json`, `test.log`, and attempt outcome.

| Attempt | Stored result | Evidence audit |
|---|---:|---|
| SPEC-001/1 | PASS v1 | Acceptance claims match diff and test result. Legacy format has no `criteria[]`. Auxiliary claim that the separate repo suite passed is not backed by a retained suite log; it was only asserted in the review request. |
| SPEC-002/1 | PASS v1 | Supported; four acceptance claims match diff/test. No `criteria[]` in v1. |
| SPEC-003/1 | PASS v1 | Supported; five acceptance claims match diff/test. No `criteria[]` in v1. |
| SPEC-003/2 | PASS, 5/5 MET | Supported. |
| SPEC-005/1 | PASS, 5/5 MET | Supported. |
| SPEC-007/1 | PASS, 5/5 MET | Supported. |
| SPEC-008/1 | PASS, 5/5 MET | Supported. |
| SPEC-008/2 | PASS, 5/5 MET | Supported. |
| SPEC-009/1 | PASS, 5/5 MET | Supported. |
| SPEC-012/1 | PASS, 4/4 MET | Supported. |
| SPEC-014/1 | PASS, 5/5 MET | Supported; test log records `PASS delegation_report.sh`. |
| SPEC-015/1 | PASS, 7/7 MET | **False/unsupported**, as detailed above. |
| SPEC-016/1 | PASS, 16/16 MET | Claims match diff/test. Attempt was later rejected for a moved base, not merged: [result.json:11](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-016/1/result.json:11). |
| SPEC-016/2 | `{}` | Not a PASS. Correctly recorded as `failed_review` / `malformed`: [result.json:11](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-016/2/result.json:11). |
| SPEC-016/3 | PASS v3, 16/16 MET | Supported; bound replacement attempt passed and merged. |

Thus:

- 15 review files inspected.
- 14 contain PASS.
- At least 1 of 14 PASSes is false.
- No other acceptance-criterion contradiction was found.
- SPEC-001 contains one unsupported auxiliary “repo suite passed” assertion, but its actual acceptance verdict remains supported by the required individual test and diff.

## 3. Root cause

This was primarily an orchestrator evidence bug, not an independent model hallucination.

### The reviewer was denied the decisive evidence

The dispatcher writes `test.log` and checks only the process return code at [dispatch.py:935](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:935)–[951](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:951). It does not recognize skipped tests.

`review()` then supplies only:

> `test_command: ./scripts/test exited 0`

at [dispatch.py:1186](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1186)–[1188](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1188). It does not include `test.log`, skip counts, executed test IDs, or assertion counts.

That exact misleading summary appears in the archived request at [review-request.txt:54](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/raw/review-request.txt:54)–[57](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/.orchestrator/attempts/SPEC-015/1/raw/review-request.txt:57). The literal return-code statement was true, but it semantically misrepresented “no failing shell process” as “the required tests ran and passed.”

Because filesystem tools are deliberately denied at [dispatch.py:1191](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1191)–[1200](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1200), the reviewer could not open the log and correct the summary.

### Schema validation checks shape, not completeness or truth

The schema requires only `criteria.minItems: 1` at [verdict.schema.json:8](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/verdict.schema.json:8)–[11](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/verdict.schema.json:11). “One entry per acceptance criterion” is merely a description.

Consequences:

- A 16-criterion spec can receive one fabricated `MET` entry and remain schema-valid.
- Criterion text need not equal any acceptance criterion.
- Evidence need only be a nonempty string.
- Duplicate, omitted, reordered, or invented criteria pass validation.

`evaluate_binary_review()` checks only the criteria actually supplied and accepts PASS if none of those have a non-`MET` result: [dispatch.py:1106](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1106)–[1116](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1116). It does not know the spec’s criterion count or identities.

It also requires scope/regression/security findings merely to be nonempty. A PASS could contain `security_findings: "Critical exploitable RCE"` and still pass this function.

### Binding proves identity, not honesty

`validate_review_verdict()` validates schema and matches `spec_digest`, `base_sha`, and `worker_commit` at [dispatch.py:1119](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1119)–[1134](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1134).

That proves the JSON names the intended change. It does not prove:

- tests executed,
- evidence supports the claims,
- every acceptance criterion is represented,
- findings are consistent with PASS,
- or the reviewer resisted prompt injection.

### Worker-controlled diff remains an untrusted prompt channel

The worker’s diff is read at [dispatch.py:1141](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1141) and concatenated directly into the reviewer prompt at [dispatch.py:1188](/srv/codexwork/selfreflect/scripts/dispatch.py:1188). A malicious changed file can contain reviewer-directed instructions. Tool denial limits filesystem damage but does not stop prompt injection into the verdict itself.

I found no such injection in these attempts, so this was not the observed SPEC-015 cause. It is nevertheless an unsound path that binding and schema validation do not mitigate.

## Highest-leverage fix

Replace the exit-code-only test summary with a trusted, machine-enforced test attestation:

- required test IDs must report actual execution and PASS;
- `SKIP`, missing tests, or zero executed assertions fail before review;
- retain and provide that structured attestation—or at minimum the full `test.log`—to the reviewer.

For SPEC-015, this would have stopped the attempt deterministically at the test gate. Merely improving the reviewer prompt or model would still leave the orchestrator certifying skipped tests as passes.

The reviewer was not given accurate evidence and then independently hallucinated a contradiction. It was lied to by omission and semantic overstatement in the orchestrator’s own evidence summary, and the validator was incapable of detecting the resulting false PASS.

INVESTIGATION COMPLETE

